The paper discusses techniques for improving the performance of scientific applications on distributed-memory systems, which are typically studied in the Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing (cs.DC) sub-category. The focus is on loop self-scheduling, which is a common optimization technique in scientific computing, and this is related to Performance (cs.PF) and Mathematical Software (cs.MS) sub-categories. The paper also discusses the use of hybrid programming approaches, which are related to Programming Languages (cs.PL) and Software Engineering (cs.SE) sub-categories.
